# Find other NA's location
def null_cell(df):
    dfx = df2.copy()
    missing_values = dfx.isnull().sum()
    missing_values_per = dfx.isnull().sum() / dfx.isnull().count()
    null_values = pd.concat([missing_values, missing_values_per],axis=1, keys = ['the_null','the_null_perc'])
    null_values = null_values.sort_values('the_null',ascending=False)
    return null_values[null_values['the_null']>0]

fill_list = (null_cell(df)).index

3. Random Forest Modeling¶

What is Random forest ?

Random forest is a type of bagging, which avoids the problem of overfitting by randomly selecting multiple subsets and averaging the results of each subset tree model.

In [ ]:
from sklearn import preprocessing
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

model = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=6, random_state=0, n_estimators=10)
model.fit(X_train, Y_train)

4. SHAP¶

SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) is a game-theoretic approach for explaining the effect of each variable in any machine learning model on the outcome in a similar way to regression models. It uses the classical Shapley values from game theory and their associated extensions to relate optimal credit allocation to local explanations.

4.1 Variable importance¶

In [ ]:
import shap
shap_values = shap.TreeExplainer(model).shap_values(X_train)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train, plot_type="bar")

Based on the visualization results, it can be seen that the top 3 variables with the greatest influence on the results are TD013, AP003, and AP004, and that the weight of AP004 is much higher than that the other variables. AP004 is approximately twice the weight of the fourth variable CD123.

Among them, TD013 represents the number of times a user has participated in P2P business in the last 6 months, AP003 indicates the user's education level, and AP004 represents the length of time of the loan. However, it is not yet possible to see whether these variables have a positive or negative effect on y.

4.2 Summary Plot¶

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
f = plt.figure()
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train)
f.savefig("/summary_plot1.png", bbox_inches='tight', dpi=600)

We can see that the top-to-bottom ordering of the variables is the same as the importance graph of the variables. This graph above can give us more information, for example, among the first three variables, TD013 and AP004 have a positive effect on the target value, while AP003 has a negative effect. And when the target value higher, the rask of recovering the loan for the bank is also higher.

Combining the meanings of the variables, the results of the random forest model can be explained as follow:

The customer who less involved in P2P business in the past 6 months, the higher the education level and the shorter the loan cycle the more likely to pay off the loan.

4.3 Dependence Plot¶

In [ ]:
# No.1: TD013
shap.dependence_plot('TD013', shap_values, X_train)

When checking the 1st important variable TD013, the system automatically chose AP003 as the second variables, and TD013 has the positive effect on the target value.

The above graph shows the relationship between TD013 and AP003, i.e., highly educated individuals with 0 P2P experience in the past 6 months are unlikely to be applicants for non-performing loans, and vice versa.

In [ ]:
# No.2: AP003
shap.dependence_plot('AP003', shap_values, X_train)

When checking the 2nd important variable AP003, the system automatically chose TD013 as the second variables, and AP003 has the negative effect on the target value.

The above graph shows the relationship between TD013 and AP003, i.e., highly educated individuals with 0 P2P experience in the past 6 months are unlikely to be applicants for non-performing loans, while individuals with more than 3 P2P experiences in the past 6 months and received lower education are less likely to be applicants for non-performing loans.

In [ ]:
# No.3: AP004
shap.dependence_plot('AP004', shap_values, X_train)

When checking the 3rd important variable AP004, the system automatically chose TD013 as the second variables, and AP004 has the negative effect on the target value.

The above graph shows the relationship between TD013 and AP004, i.e., individuals who choose short-term loan with little P2P experience in the past 6 months are unlikely to be applicants for non-performing loans, while individuals who choose long-term loan with more P2P experiences in the past 6 months are likely to be applicants for non-performing loans.

In [ ]:
# No.4: CD123
shap.dependence_plot('CD123', shap_values, X_train, xmin=0, xmax="percentile(99)")

When checking the 4th important variable CD123, the system automatically chose AP003 as the second variables.

The variable CD123 represents the number of calls from outboundary in the last 3 months that the client received, and CD123 has the negative effect on the target value.

For this graph, I set the x-axis to range above 0 and below 99% to exclude the effect of special values and filled in -999. The graph above shows that individuals receiving higher education are concentrated near to the 0 SHAP value and are evenly distributed across the CD123. When CD123 is below 50, some of the red points are at significantly higher than others.

The figure also shows that these two variables are less influential than the other combinations in determining whether a person is a person who cannot pay one’s debts.

4.4 Force Plot¶

In [ ]:
# Get the predictions and put them with the test data.
X_output = X_test.copy()
X_output.loc[:,'predict'] = np.round(model.predict(X_output),2)

# Randomly pick some observations
random_picks = np.arange(1,330,50) # Every 50 rows
S = X_output.iloc[random_picks]

shap.initjs()

def shap_plot(j):
    explainerModel = shap.TreeExplainer(model) # base value
    shap_values_Model = explainerModel.shap_values(S) # SHAP value
    p = shap.force_plot(explainerModel.expected_value, shap_values_Model[j], S.iloc[[j]])
    return(p)

shap_plot(0)
